LAMP Stack Installation and Configuration Documentation
Overview

This was my experience of setting up a LAMP stack on my VM hosted on Google Cloud. A LAMP stack stands for: Linux (operating system), Apache (web server), MySQL (database server), PHP (server-side scripting language). The goal of these weeks was to ensure they function together as a complete web stack. 
Before installing any software, I updated the package list:
“sudo apt update”
This completed successfully with no errors.
To install the Apache web server:
“sudo apt install apache2”
When prompted, I entered Y to confirm.
Verify Apache Status
“systemctl status apache2”
Output showed:
Active: active (running)
Then to verify it was working I installed elinks
“sudo apt install elinks”
And when I went to the external IP:
http://34.75.80.108/
It displayed the correct page.
I then went to the next step to create a webpage
“cd /var/www/html/
sudo mv index.html index.original.html
sudo nano index.html”
I didn’t get creative with my html, I just pasted from the text 
“<html>
<head>
<title>My first web page using Apache</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Welcome</h1>
<p>Welcome to my web site.
I created this site using the Apache HTTP server.</p>
</body>
</html>”
From my link of http://34.75.80.108/index.original.html it worked
To install php I ran
“sudo apt install php libapache2-mod-php
sudo systemctl restart apache2”
Then confirmed the version with 
“php -v”
Then
“systemctl status apache2”
For the start of the next step I entered
“cd /var/www/html/
sudo nano info.php”
And added this text
“<?php
phpinfo();
?>”
Then I opened to check it at http://34.75.80.108/info.php 
It was hard not to type in “https”
After confirming I deleted the file with 
“sudo rm /var/www/html/info.php”
I edited the dir.conf file as requested 
“cd /etc/apache2/mods-available/
sudo cp dir.conf dir.conf.bak
sudo nano dir.conf”
then changed the line to the desired order:
DirectoryIndex index.php index.html index.cgi index.pl index.xhtml index.htm
DirectoryIndex index.php index.html”
To test it was working I ran
“apachectl configtest”
cd /var/www/html/
