	Through the process of installing and configuring a LAMP stack on an Ubuntu virtual machine, I gained some understanding of how web servers, databases, and server-side scripting languages work together. While the individual steps of installing Apache, MySQL, and PHP were relatively straightforward, the overall experience was frustrating I am definitely out of my element. The troubleshooting was something I would have really enjoyed if I would have stuck with something in the tech field since I love puzzles. 
	One of the most important things I learned is how each part of the LAMP stack serves a distinct role. Apache functions as the web server, meaning it is responsible for receiving requests from a client (such as a web browser) and returning the appropriate content. PHP acts as the server-side scripting language, allowing the server to generate dynamic content rather than serving only HTML pages. MySQL provides a structured way to store and retrieve data, which is required for most modern web applications. Seeing these components work together helped me better understand how a simple browser request can trigger a chain of processes behind the scenes, ultimately producing a fully ready web page. Another key takeaway from this process is the importance of verifying each step rather than assuming everything is working correctly. The step-by-step verification approach made it much easier to identify where problems occurred and prevented small issues from becoming larger ones later in the setup. Troubleshooting was a major part of the learning experience. Several errors occurred during the process, including permission issues when trying to create files in the web root directory, password policy errors when creating MySQL users, and authentication failures when attempting to log into MySQL. Each of these issues required me to slow down and think critically about what the system was doing and why it was failing. For instance, the “permission denied” error reinforced the concept of Linux file ownership and the need to use different privileges in certain directories. The MySQL password policy error demonstrated that systems often enforce security standards by default, requiring stronger passwords than expected. Additionally, the “access denied” error when logging into MySQL highlighted the importance of understanding authentication methods and properly configuring user credentials.
	Lessons involved configuration files and how small changes can significantly impact system behavior. Editing Apache’s dir.conf file to prioritize index.php over index.html demonstrated how server behavior can be customized to meet specific needs of the user. Similarly, running the mysql_secure_installation script showed how default database settings can be adjusted to improve security. These experiences emphasized that installing software is only half of the battle, proper configuration is what makes the system functional.
	I realized how important it is to pay attention to syntax and command structure, especially when working in the terminal or within MySQL. A small mistake, such as repeating part of a command or missing punctuation in a PHP file, can lead to confusing errors.
	Overall, this project provided hands-on experience with web server administration and reinforced the importance of patience, attention to detail, and systematic troubleshooting. It also gave me a foundation for understanding how web applications are built and maintained.
